> Ironically the toasts will be even better if your bread is a bit stale when you make them so if this is the last meal of the week then all the better!

Boil @water{600%ml} with the @vegetable stock pot{1}. Drain and thoroughly rinse the @organic lentils{1}. Peel and finely dice the @carrot{1/3}, @potato{1} and one clove of @garlic{2%cloves}. Finely dice the @celery stick{1} and finely chop the @chestnut mushrooms{2}.

Soak the @dried porcini mushrooms{2} in half a cup of warm water.

Heat 1 tbsp of @olive oil{1%tbsp} and @butter{1%tsp} (if you have it) in a #pot on medium-low heat. Gently fry the carrot, celery and diced garlic with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Pull the leaves from the @thyme{3} stalk and add these too.

> Don't let the vegetables brown and reduce heat if necessary.

After ~{5%minutes} add in the diced potato and the chestnut mushrooms. Lift the porcini from the water and chop up finely before adding to the pan. Add another pinch of salt and pepper and keep the porcini water. Preheat the #oven to 190 degrees.

After ~{5%minutes} add the stock and porcini water to the pan. Bubble the liquid away on medium heat until it has thickened up (~{15%minutes}).

Slice the @wholemeal baguette{1} widthways into slices just under 1cm thick and place in the oven. Bake the bread for around ~{8%minutes} until crispy. Chop the remaining clove of garlic in half and rub this over each piece of warm bread.

Drizzle a little @olive oil{} and a pinch of salt and pepper on each piece of bread. Top them with the @hard Italian style cheese{2%tbsp}(grated) and put back in the oven until the cheese melts.

Add the lentils to the soup and cook for ~{1%minute} before removing from the heat. Stir in the @double cream{4%tbsp} and add more salt and pepper to taste. Serve the soup with the Italian toasts on top and dive in!